            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Miller has always occupied the spaces in between. The son of a quiet, methodical Japanese mother who worked as a lab technician and a boisterous, kind-hearted German-American father who was a union carpenter, Kai grew up in a modest Daly City home filled with two distinct cultures. He was never fully one or the other, a reality that fostered a deep sense of observation and empathy from a young age. His identity was further shaped by his younger brother, Leo, who was born with a sensory processing disorder. Watching Leo struggle with everyday tasks that others took for granted planted a seed in Kai\u2019s mind.\n\nAfter high school, Kai wasn\u2019t drawn to a four-year university. He felt a pull toward practical, hands-on work. He spent a few years working various jobs\u2014barista, bike messenger, hardware store clerk\u2014before the memory of Leo\u2019s occupational therapy sessions resurfaced. He saw a path that felt purposeful. Enrolling in an Associate's degree program for Occupational Therapy Assistants was the turning point. The work clicked immediately; it was a perfect blend of structure, creativity, and direct human impact.\n\nNow 38, Kai has built a life of quiet intention in San Francisco. He works for a K-12 school district, helping children develop the skills to navigate their world, from holding a pencil to managing classroom anxiety. His $82,000 income requires careful budgeting, but his needs are simple. He lives in a small, rent-controlled one-bedroom in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood he loves for its foggy mornings and proximity to Golden Gate Park.\n\nHis daily routine is his ritual. The 3.5-mile bicycle commute to a school in the Western Addition is his morning meditation, a time to observe the city waking up. After a demanding day of work, he enjoys cooking simple Japanese or German-inspired meals, tending to his collection of houseplants, or meeting a small circle of close friends for a low-key trivia night.\n\nKai\u2019s aspirations aren't grand; they are deep. He hopes to one day earn a specialized certification in sensory integration. He dreams of a stable, loving partnership with someone who values connection over status. More than anything, he wants to continue being a calm, steadying presence for the children he serves, offering them the same patience and understanding he once saw give his own brother a foothold in the world."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten, watching his younger brother, Leo, have a complete meltdown on the floor. It wasn't a tantrum; it was the seam on his sock. His mother was trying to soothe him while Kai just stared, a hot spike of protectiveness shooting through him. In that moment of his brother\u2019s overwhelming distress over something so small, Kai felt a deep, wordless vow form: to understand the things nobody else could see. It was the birth of his patience and the first true stirring of his life\u2019s purpose.\n\n***\n\n2.\nAt twelve, he stood beside his mother at the kitchen sink as she washed rice. Her motions were a quiet, hypnotic ritual: the swirl of her hand, the cloudy water draining away, the gentle *clink* of the grains. She explained that this step, this careful washing, was the secret to good rice. It wasn't about the recipe, but the attention. This memory became his blueprint for life, teaching him that the most profound results often come from quiet, diligent, and loving preparation, a principle he applies to both his cooking and his work.\n\n***\n\n3.\nHe was 22, a bike messenger, feeling directionless and lost in the city\u2019s concrete canyons. During one frantic delivery, he paused at the top of Potrero Hill, gasping for breath. Below him, the entire city hummed, a vast and indifferent machine. But from that height, it was also beautiful and strangely quiet. For the first time, he didn't feel crushed by it, but a part of its complex rhythm. That moment of clarity taught him he could find his own stillness, his own perspective, even in the middle of chaos.\n\n***\n\n4.\nThe turning point came in a bland classroom when he was 26. His occupational therapy professor was explaining proprioceptive input\u2014how the body understands its position in space. The professor described a child who crashed into things not out of clumsiness, but from a need to *feel* their own edges. Suddenly, Leo\u2019s entire childhood clicked into focus. It wasn't just a disorder; it was a need. Giving a name to the struggle was like being handed a map, and he knew right then he was finally on the right path.\n\n***\n\n5.\nShortly after moving into his Inner Richmond apartment in his early thirties, he took a walk into Golden Gate Park on a thick, foggy morning. He couldn't see more than fifty feet ahead. The sound of the city vanished, replaced by the drip of moisture from eucalyptus trees and the muffled call of a raven. He felt enveloped, safe, and utterly at peace. The fog wasn't hiding the world, it was softening it. It was then he knew he was truly home, having found a place that mirrored his own calm soul."
